Defining Tcl Procedures
Because the Vivado Design Suite provides a full Tcl interpreter built into the tool, creating new custom commands and procedures is a simple task. You can write Tcl scripts that can be loaded and run from the Vivado IDE, or you can write procedures, to act like new Tcl commands, taking arguments, checking for errors...
proc helloProc { arg1 } {
    # This is a comment inside the body of the procedure
    puts "Hello World! Arg1 is $arg1"
}

Defining Tcl Procedures
A procedure usually has predefined arguments. Each of them can optionally have a default value. When an argument has a default value, it does not need to be specified when calling the procedure if all the mandatory preceding arguments are specified. A procedure returns an empty string unless the return command is us...
proc reportWorstViolations { nbrPaths corner delayType } {
    report_timing -max_paths $nbrPaths -corner $corner -delay_type $delayType -nworst 1
}

Defining Tcl Procedures
The next example is a different form of the same procedure, where the last two of the three arguments have a default value. The default value for corner is Slow, and the default value for delayType is Max. With default values specified in the definition of the procedure, the corner and delayType arguments are option...
proc reportWorstViolations { nbrPaths { corner Slow } { delayType Max } }
{
    report_timing -max_paths $nbrPaths -corner $corner -delay_type $delayType -nworst 1
}

Defining Tcl Procedures
The following example is an illustration of a procedure that has one mandatory argument, nbrPath, but that can also accept any number of additional arguments. This uses the Tcl keyword args in the list of arguments when defining the procedure. The args keyword is a Tcl list that can have any number of elements, incl...
proc reportWorstViolations { nbrPaths args } {
    eval report_timing -max_paths $nbrPaths $args
}

