    return -code ok "my_command1 result"
}

get\_property and Sorted Lists
While some Tcl commands expect a design object, other commands might expect a string input. The Vivado Design Suite has been implemented to allow design objects to be passed directly to Tcl commands, even those expecting a string argument. In this case, the hierarchical name of the design object is passed to the Tcl...
if {{[regexp {.*enable.*} $MyObject]} { ... }
if {{[regexp {.*enable.*} [get_property NAME $MyObject]]}} { ... }

Formatting Lists of Objects
The list of elements (strings or objects) returned by get\_property is ordered based on the input list of objects. It also has the same number of elements. This property can be used to iterate with the Tcl command foreach through multiple lists at once. In the code above, the command get\_property LOC \$cell is exec...
set cells [get_cells -hier -filter {...}]
foreach cell $cells loc [get_property LOC $cells] {
...
}

Finding Vivado Tcl Commands by Options
✎ Note: When converting a Vivado collection of objects into a string representation, not all the objects have to be included in the string representation. The number of objects to be included in the string representation is defined with the parameter tcl.collectionResultDisplayLimit (default: 500). Refer to section...
proc findCmd {option} {
    foreach cmd [lsort [info commands *]] {
    catch {
    if {[regexp "$option" [help -syntax $cmd]]} {
    puts $cmd
    }
    }
    }
}; # End proc

Getting User Input
One way to improve runtime is to write code efficiently such that a container is built and a command runs on the entire container versus running the command within a loop on each item that would be part of the container. The following example illustrates this and is similar to that seen in the Creating Custom Design...
foreach bram [get_cells -hier -filter {PRIMITIVE_SUBGROUP == bram}] {
    set bwidth [get_property WRITE_WIDTH_B $bram]
    if { $bwidth > 36 } {
    highlight_object -color red [get_cells $bram]
    }; # End IF
}; # End FOR

